{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15419"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54785"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7630"},{"type":"tags","id":"7633"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19672"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMallory-Denk bodies are eosinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions found within hepatocytes in various liver diseases. They appear as irregular, rope-like structures on microscopic examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of Mallory-Denk bodies?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aggregated cytokeratin intermediate filaments","Accumulated copper-protein complexes","Crystallised bilirubin deposits","Condensed glycogen granules","Viral protein inclusions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMallory-Denk bodies are composed of \u003Cstrong\u003Eaggregated cytokeratin intermediate filaments\u003C/strong\u003E that accumulate within hepatocytes due to protein degradation dysfunction and oxidative stress. These aggregates also contain ubiquitin and other stress-related proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulated copper-protein complexes\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of Wilson disease but are not components of Mallory-Denk bodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrystallised bilirubin deposits\u003C/strong\u003E form in bile ducts during gallstone formation but are not found within hepatocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondensed glycogen granules\u003C/strong\u003E accumulate in glycogen storage diseases but do not form Mallory-Denk bodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral protein inclusions\u003C/strong\u003E may be seen in viral hepatitis but are distinct from Mallory-Denk bodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMallory-Denk bodies are most commonly associated with alcoholic liver disease and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis, though they can occur in other conditions causing hepatocyte injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mallory-Denk bodies are intracellular aggregates of misfolded cytokeratin intermediate filaments that form in stressed hepatocytes","Mallory-Denk bodies are commonly seen in alcoholic liver disease and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis","Formation occurs due to protein degradation dysfunction and oxidative stress in hepatocytes"],"references":["Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kurtovic E, Limaiem F. Mallory Bodies. 2024 Apr 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31424884.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54785"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54785"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:51:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:53:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8110"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69332"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gr